# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cluster-analysis-stats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis refers to a family of algorithms and tasks rather than one specific algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be achieved by various algorithms that differ significantly in their understanding of what constitutes a cluster and how to efficiently find them.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Popular notions of clusters include groups with small distances between cluster members, dense areas of the data space, intervals or particular statistical distributions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Clustering can therefore be formulated as a multi-objective optimization problem.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The appropriate clustering algorithm and parameter settings (including parameters such as the distance function to use, a density threshold or the number of expected clusters) depend on the individual data set and intended use of the results.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis as such is not an automatic task, but an iterative process of knowledge discovery or interactive multi-objective optimization that involves trial and failure.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It is often necessary to modify data preprocessing and model parameters until the result achieves the desired properties.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides the term *clustering*, there are a number of terms with similar meanings, including *automatic classification*, *numerical taxonomy*, *botryology* (from Greek: βότρυς 'grape'), *typological analysis*, and *community detection*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The subtle differences are often in the use of the results: while in data mining, the resulting groups are the matter of interest, in automatic classification the resulting discriminative power is of interest.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis originated in anthropology by Driver and Kroeber in 1932 and introduced to psychology by Joseph Zubin in 1938 and Robert Tryon in 1939 and famously used by Cattell beginning in 1943 for trait theory classification in personality psychology.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a "cluster" cannot be precisely defined, which is one of the reasons why there are so many clustering algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] There is a common denominator: a group of data objects.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] However, different researchers employ different cluster models, and for each of these cluster models again different algorithms can be given.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a cluster, as found by different algorithms, varies significantly in its properties.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Understanding these "cluster models" is key to understanding the differences between the various algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A "clustering" is essentially a set of such clusters, usually containing all objects in the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, it may specify the relationship of the clusters to each other, for example, a hierarchy of clusters embedded in each other.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] As listed above, clustering algorithms can be categorized based on their cluster model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The following overview will only list the most prominent examples of clustering algorithms, as there are possibly over 100 published clustering algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Not all provide models for their clusters and can thus not easily be categorized.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] An overview of algorithms explained in Wikipedia can be found in the list of statistics algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The most appropriate clustering algorithm for a particular problem often needs to be chosen experimentally, unless there is a mathematical reason to prefer one cluster model over another.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm that is designed for one kind of model will generally fail on a data set that contains a radically different kind of model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means cannot find non-convex clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Most traditional clustering methods assume the clusters exhibit a spherical, elliptical or convex shape.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering, also known as hierarchical clustering, is based on the idea that objects are more related to nearby objects than to those farther away.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] These algorithms form clusters by connecting objects based on their distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster can be understood in terms of the maximum distance required to connect its elements.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] At different distance thresholds, different cluster groupings appear.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] These groupings can be visualized using a dendrogram, a tree-like diagram that shows how clusters merge as the distance increases.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This explains the term "hierarchical clustering": instead of producing a single partition of the data set, the algorithm builds a hierarchy of clusters that merge at different distances.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In a dendrogram, the y-axis shows the distance at which clusters merge, while the x-axis arranges objects so that clusters appear as continuous branches.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering is a family of methods that differ in how distances between clusters are computed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In addition to choosing a distance function, the user must also select a **linkage criterion**, which determines how the distance between clusters is calculated.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Common linkage criteria include single-linkage clustering (minimum distance between points), complete linkage clustering (maximum distance), and UPGMA or WPGMA (average linkage based on mean distances).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Hierarchical clustering can be either agglomerative (starting with individual elements and merging them) or divisive (starting with the full data set and splitting it).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Identify the two closest clusters based on a chosen distance measure.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate distances between the new cluster and the remaining clusters using the selected linkage criterion.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat until all data points are merged into a single cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This process produces a full hierarchy of possible clusterings rather than a single final result.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A specific clustering can be obtained by selecting a cut level in the dendrogram, which determines how many clusters are formed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods do not produce a unique partitioning of the data set, but rather a hierarchy from which the user must choose appropriate clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] They are also sensitive to outliers, which may appear as separate clusters or cause other clusters to merge.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This effect, especially in single-linkage clustering, is known as the "chaining phenomenon".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In the general case, the complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ for agglomerative clustering and ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n-1})$ for divisive clustering, which makes them computationally expensive for large data sets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For some special cases, more efficient methods (with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known, such as SLINK for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In centroid-based clustering, each cluster is represented by a central vector, which is not necessarily a member of the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] When the number of clusters is fixed to *k*, *k*-means clustering gives a formal definition as an optimization problem: find the *k* cluster centers and assign the objects to the nearest cluster center, such that the squared distances from the cluster are minimized.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The optimization problem itself is known to be NP-hard, and thus the common approach is to search only for approximate solutions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A particularly well-known approximate method is Lloyd's algorithm, often just referred to as "*k-means algorithm*" (although another algorithm introduced this name).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It does however only find a local optimum, and is commonly run multiple times with different random initializations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Most *k*-means-type algorithms require the number of clusters – *k* – to be specified in advance, which is considered to be one of the biggest drawbacks of these algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Furthermore, the algorithms prefer clusters of approximately similar size, as they will always assign an object to the nearest centroid; often yielding improperly cut borders of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This happens primarily because the algorithm optimizes cluster centers, not cluster borders.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Assign each observation to the centroid to which it has the smallest squared Euclidean distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This results in *k* distinct groups, each containing unique observations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate centroids (see *k*-means clustering).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Exit *iff* the new centroids are equivalent to the previous iteration's centroids.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Else, repeat the algorithm, the centroids have yet to converge.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] K-means has a number of interesting theoretical properties.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] First, it partitions the data space into a structure known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Second, it is conceptually close to nearest neighbor classification, and as such is popular in machine learning.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Third, it can be seen as a variation of model-based clustering, and Lloyd's algorithm as a variation of the Expectation-maximization algorithm for this model discussed below.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The following pseudocode describes the standard iterative refinement form of *k*-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The algorithm alternates between an **assignment step**, which labels each point by its nearest centroid, and an **update step**, which recomputes each centroid as the mean of its assigned points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Convergence is guaranteed in a finite number of iterations, though the result may be a local optimum.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Centroid-based clustering problems such as *k*-means and *k*-medoids are special cases of the uncapacitated, metric facility location problem, a canonical problem in the operations research and computational geometry communities.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In a basic facility location problem (of which there are numerous variants that model more elaborate settings), the task is to find the best warehouse locations to optimally service a given set of consumers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One may view "warehouses" as cluster centroids and "consumer locations" as the data to be clustered.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This makes it possible to apply the well-developed algorithmic solutions from the facility location literature to the presently considered centroid-based clustering problem.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The clustering framework most closely related to statistics is model-based clustering, which is based on distribution models.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This approach models the data as arising from a mixture of probability distributions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It has the advantages of providing principled statistical answers to questions such as how many clusters there are, what clustering method or model to use, and how to detect and deal with outliers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] While the theoretical foundation of these methods is excellent, they suffer from overfitting unless constraints are put on the model complexity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A more complex model will usually be able to explain the data better, which makes choosing the appropriate model complexity inherently difficult.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Standard model-based clustering methods include more parsimonious models based on the eigenvalue decomposition of the covariance matrices, that provide a balance between overfitting and fidelity to the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One prominent method is known as Gaussian mixture models (using the expectation-maximization algorithm).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Here, the data set is usually modeled with a fixed (to avoid overfitting) number of Gaussian distributions that are initialized randomly and whose parameters are iteratively optimized to better fit the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This will converge to a local optimum, so multiple runs may produce different results.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In order to obtain a hard clustering, objects are often then assigned to the Gaussian distribution they most likely belong to; for soft clusterings, this is not necessary.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Distribution-based clustering produces complex models for clusters that can capture correlation and dependence between attributes.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] However, these algorithms put an extra burden on the user: for many real data sets, there may be no concisely defined mathematical model (e.g. assuming Gaussian distributions is a rather strong assumption on the data).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In density-based clustering, clusters are defined as areas of higher density than the remainder of the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects in sparse areas – that are required to separate clusters – are usually considered to be noise and border points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The most popular density-based clustering method is DBSCAN.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In contrast to many newer methods, it features a well-defined cluster model called "density-reachability".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to linkage-based clustering, it is based on connecting points within certain distance thresholds.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it only connects points that satisfy a density criterion, in the original variant defined as a minimum number of other objects within this radius.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster consists of all density-connected objects (which can form a cluster of an arbitrary shape, in contrast to many other methods) plus all objects that are within these objects' range.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] OPTICS is a generalization of DBSCAN that removes the need to choose an appropriate value for the range parameter $\varepsilon$ , and produces a hierarchical result related to that of linkage clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering combines ideas from single-linkage clustering and OPTICS, eliminating the $\varepsilon$ parameter entirely and offering performance improvements over OPTICS by using an R-tree index.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] HDBSCAN extends DBSCAN by converting it into a hierarchical clustering algorithm, and then using a technique to extract a flat clustering based in the stability of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The key drawback of DBSCAN and OPTICS is that they expect some kind of density drop to detect cluster borders.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] On data sets with, for example, overlapping Gaussian distributions – a common use case in artificial data – the cluster borders produced by these algorithms will often look arbitrary, because the cluster density decreases continuously.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set consisting of mixtures of Gaussians, these algorithms are nearly always outperformed by methods such as EM clustering that are able to precisely model this kind of data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Mean-shift is a clustering approach where each object is moved to the densest area in its vicinity, based on kernel density estimation.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Eventually, objects converge to local maxima of density.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to k-means clustering, these "density attractors" can serve as representatives for the data set, but mean-shift can detect arbitrary-shaped clusters similar to DBSCAN.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Due to the expensive iterative procedure and density estimation, mean-shift is usually slower than DBSCAN or k-Means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides that, the applicability of the mean-shift algorithm to multidimensional data is hindered by the unsmooth behaviour of the kernel density estimate, which results in over-fragmentation of cluster tails.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is used for a multi-dimensional data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In this technique, we create a grid structure, and the comparison is performed on grids (also known as cells).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is fast and has low computational complexity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] There are two types of grid-based clustering methods: STING and CLIQUE.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Randomly select a cell ‘c’, where c should not be traversed beforehand.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Calculate the density of all the neighbors of ‘c’.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] If the density of a neighboring cell is greater than threshold density then, add the cell in the cluster and repeat steps 4.2 and 4.3 till there is no neighbor with a density greater than threshold density.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat steps 2, 3, and 4 till all the cells are traversed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] With the increasing need to process Big data, the willingness to trade semantic meaning of the generated clusters for performance becomes more relevant.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, efforts have been put into improving the performance of existing algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This led to the development of pre-clustering methods such as canopy clustering, which can process huge data sets efficiently, but the resulting "clusters" are merely a rough pre-partitioning of the data set to then analyze the partitions with existing slower methods such as k-means clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For high-dimensional data, many methods fail due to the curse of dimensionality, which renders particular distance functions problematic in high-dimensional spaces.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Examples for such clustering algorithms are CLIQUE and SUBCLU.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Several different clustering systems based on mutual information have been proposed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One is Marina Meilă's *variation of information* metric; another provides hierarchical clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Using genetic algorithms, a wide range of different fit-functions can be optimized, including mutual information.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Also belief propagation, a recent development in computer science and statistical physics, has led to the creation of new types of clustering algorithms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Evaluation (or "validation") of clustering results is as difficult as the clustering itself.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Internal evaluation measures suffer from the problem that they represent functions that themselves can be seen as a clustering objective.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, one could cluster the data set by the Silhouette coefficient; except that there is no known efficient algorithm for this.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] By using such an internal measure for evaluation, one rather compares the similarity of the optimization problems, and not necessarily how useful the clustering is.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] External evaluation has similar problems: if we have such "ground truth" labels, then we would not need to cluster; and in practical applications we usually do not have such labels.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] On the other hand, the labels only reflect one possible partitioning of the data set, which does not imply that there does not exist a different, and maybe even better, clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Neither of these approaches can therefore ultimately judge the actual quality of a clustering, but this needs human evaluation, which is highly subjective.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Nevertheless, such statistics can be quite informative in identifying bad clusterings, but one should not dismiss subjective human evaluation.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] When a clustering result is evaluated based on the data that was clustered itself, this is called internal evaluation.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods usually assign the best score to the algorithm that produces clusters with high similarity within a cluster and low similarity between clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One drawback of using internal criteria in cluster evaluation is that high scores on an internal measure do not necessarily result in effective information retrieval applications.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, this evaluation is biased towards algorithms that use the same cluster model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering naturally optimizes object distances, and a distance-based internal criterion will likely overrate the resulting clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, the internal evaluation measures are best suited to get some insight into situations where one algorithm performs better than another, but this shall not imply that one algorithm produces more valid results than another.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Validity as measured by such an index depends on the claim that this kind of structure exists in the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm designed for some kind of models has no chance if the data set contains a radically different set of models, or if the evaluation measures a radically different criterion.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering can only find convex clusters, and many evaluation indexes assume convex clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set with non-convex clusters neither the use of *k*-means, nor of an evaluation criterion that assumes convexity, is sound.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Many internal evaluation measures are based on the intuition that items in the same cluster should be more similar than items in different clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dunn index aims to identify dense and well-separated clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It is defined as the ratio between the minimal inter-cluster distance to maximal intra-cluster distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] where *d*(*i*,*j*) represents the distance between clusters *i* and *j*, and *d* '(*k*) measures the intra-cluster distance of cluster *k*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The inter-cluster distance *d*(*i*,*j*) between two clusters may be any number of distance measures, such as the distance between the centroids of the clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Similarly, the intra-cluster distance *d* '(*k*) may be measured in a variety of ways, such as the maximal distance between any pair of elements in cluster *k*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Since internal criterion seek clusters with high intra-cluster similarity and low inter-cluster similarity, algorithms that produce clusters with high Dunn index are more desirable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The silhouette coefficient contrasts the average distance to elements in the same cluster with the average distance to elements in other clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects with a high silhouette value are considered well clustered, objects with a low value may be outliers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This index works well with *k*-means clustering, and is also used to determine the optimal number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This matrix consider pairs of objects: the distance between the pair as a scoring function and the partition pairs defined true positive, true negatives, false negatives and true negatives by considering if pairs are in the same clusters of not.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This index borrow the same characteristics as the AUC in the supervised scenario including an expected value of 0.5 and vizualisation of results.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In external evaluation, clustering results are evaluated based on data that was not used for clustering, such as known class labels and external benchmarks.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Such benchmarks consist of a set of pre-classified items, and these sets are often created by (expert) humans.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Thus, the benchmark sets can be thought of as a gold standard for evaluation.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] These types of evaluation methods measure how close the clustering is to the predetermined benchmark classes.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it has recently been discussed whether this is adequate for real data, or only on synthetic data sets with a factual ground truth, since classes can contain internal structure, the attributes present may not allow separation of clusters or the classes may contain anomalies.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, from a knowledge discovery point of view, the reproduction of known knowledge may not necessarily be the intended result.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In the special scenario of constrained clustering, where meta information (such as class labels) is used already in the clustering process, the hold-out of information for evaluation purposes is non-trivial.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A number of measures are adapted from variants used to evaluate classification tasks.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In place of counting the number of times a class was correctly assigned to a single data point (known as true positives), such *pair counting* metrics assess whether each pair of data points that is truly in the same cluster is predicted to be in the same cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Purity is a measure of the extent to which clusters contain a single class.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Its calculation can be thought of as follows: For each cluster, count the number of data points from the most common class in said cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Now take the sum over all clusters and divide by the total number of data points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This measure doesn't penalize having many clusters, and more clusters will make it easier to produce a high purity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A purity score of 1 is always possible by putting each data point in its own cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Also, purity doesn't work well for imbalanced data, where even poorly performing clustering algorithms will give a high purity value.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, if a size 1000 dataset consists of two classes, one containing 999 points and the other containing 1 point, then every possible partition will have a purity of at least 99.9%.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Rand index computes how similar the clusters (returned by the clustering algorithm) are to the benchmark classifications.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $TN$ is the number of true negatives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The instances being counted here are the number of correct *pairwise* assignments.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] That is, $TP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition and in the ground truth partition, $FP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition but not in the ground truth partition etc.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] If the dataset is of size N, then $TP+TN+FP+FN={\binom {N}{2}}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One issue with the Rand index is that false positives and false negatives are equally weighted.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This may be an undesirable characteristic for some clustering applications.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure addresses this concern, as does the chance-corrected adjusted Rand index.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure can be used to balance the contribution of false negatives by weighting recall through a parameter $\beta \geq 0$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Let **precision** and **recall** (both external evaluation measures in themselves) be defined as follows: $P={\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}$ $R={\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}$ where P is the precision rate and R is the recall rate.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In other words, recall has no impact on the F-measure when $\beta =0$ , and increasing $\beta$ allocates an increasing amount of weight to recall in the final F-measure.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Also $TN$ is not taken into account and can vary from 0 upward without bound.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is used to quantify the similarity between two datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index takes on a value between 0 and 1.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] An index of 1 means that the two dataset are identical, and an index of 0 indicates that the datasets have no common elements.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is defined by the following formula: $J(A,B)={\frac {|A\cap B|}{|A\cup B|}}={\frac {TP}{TP+FP+FN}}$ This is simply the number of unique elements common to both sets divided by the total number of unique elements in both sets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Note that $TN$ is not taken into account.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dice symmetric measure doubles the weight on $TP$ while still ignoring $TN$ : $DSC={\frac {2TP}{2TP+FP+FN}}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Fowlkes–Mallows index computes the similarity between the clusters returned by the clustering algorithm and the benchmark classifications.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Fowlkes–Mallows index the more similar the clusters and the benchmark classifications are.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be computed using the following formula: $FM={\sqrt {{\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}\cdot {\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}}}$ where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The $FM$ index is the geometric mean of the precision and recall P and R , and is thus also known as the G-measure, while the F-measure is their harmonic mean.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Moreover, precision and recall are also known as Wallace's indices $B^{I}$ and $B^{II}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Chance normalized versions of recall, precision and G-measure correspond to Informedness, Markedness and Matthews Correlation and relate strongly to Kappa.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The Chi index is an external validation index that measure the clustering results by applying the chi-squared statistic.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] This index scores positively the fact that the labels are as sparse as possible across the clusters, i.e., that each cluster has as few different labels as possible.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Chi Index the greater the relationship between the resulting clusters and the label used.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The mutual information is an information theoretic measure of how much information is shared between a clustering and a ground-truth classification that can detect a non-linear similarity between two clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Normalized mutual information is a family of corrected-for-chance variants of this that has a reduced bias for varying cluster numbers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] A confusion matrix can be used to quickly visualize the results of a classification (or clustering) algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] It shows how different a cluster is from the gold standard cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] To measure cluster tendency is to measure to what degree clusters exist in the data to be clustered, and may be performed as an initial test, before attempting clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] One way to do this is to compare the data against random data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] On average, random data should not have clusters .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] uniformly randomly distributed data points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] With this definition, uniform random data should tend to have values near to 0.5, and clustered data should tend to have values nearer to 1.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] , making this statistic largely useless in application (as real data never is remotely uniform).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] As clustering algorithms are increasingly deployed by corporations and governmental organizations to categorize populations and automate decisions with real world data, concerns regarding algorithmic bias have become more prevalent.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Because clustering is a form of unsupervised learning, it identifies patterns within existing data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Consequently, these models can inadvertently reinforce historical inequalities already existent in the training datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] In response, researchers have developed "Fair Clustering" frameworks, such as the Fairlet approach, which ensures that each cluster maintains a balanced representation of protected groups relative to the overall population.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Under the legal doctrine of disparate impact, a process is considered discriminatory if it results in disproportionately adverse outcomes for a protected class, even if the algorithm is facially neutral (i.e., it does not explicitly use attributes like race or gender).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Unfairness often occurs through proxy variables.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] For instance, even if a dataset is stripped of race, a clustering algorithm might use ZIP codes or educational background as features.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] Because these variables are often highly related to economic status and ethnicity, the resulting clusters will effectively segregate individuals by these characteristics.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p01] The application of clustering in predictive policing has demonstrated how historical bias in data can create feedback loops.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p02] Cluster analysis is used for data analysis across a wide range of fields.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p02] In the natural sciences, techniques such as hierarchical clustering, *k*-means,dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis (PCA), and t-SNE are frequently used to make sense of the dense data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p02] In computing and technology applications, clustering is the driving force behind machine learning's unsupervised learning, and is embedded in systems ranging from search engines to recommendation platforms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p02] Common algorithms in this field include *k*-means, DBSCAN, mean shift, and spectral clustering, often applied after feature extraction or embedding, which are steps that map raw data, such as text, images, sensor logs, into a vector space amenable to distance based grouping.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/cluster-analysis-p02] In business and the social sciences, clustering is most often applied to tabular survey and transaction data, where the aim is to segment populations into consumer groups, create detailed market analysis insights, or illustrate voter preferences.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] In 2014, the algorithm was awarded the Test of Time Award (an award given to algorithms which have received substantial attention in theory and practice) at the leading data mining conference, ACM SIGKDD.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] As of July 2020, the follow-up paper "DBSCAN Revisited, Revisited: Why and How You Should (Still) Use DBSCAN" appears in the list of the 8 most downloaded articles of the prestigious ACM Transactions on Database Systems (TODS) journal.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Another follow-up, **HDBSCAN***, was initially published by Ricardo J.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Campello, David Moulavi, and Jörg Sander in 2013, then expanded upon with Arthur Zimek in 2015.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] It revises some of the original decisions such as the border points, and produces a hierarchical instead of a flat result.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Ling published a closely related algorithm in "The Theory and Construction of k-Clusters" in *The Computer Journal* with an estimated runtime complexity of O(n³).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN has a worst-case complexity of O(n²).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The database-oriented range-query formulation of DBSCAN allows for index acceleration.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The algorithms slightly differ in their handling of border points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Consider a set of points in some space to be clustered.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Let ε be a parameter specifying the radius of a neighborhood with respect to some point.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Now if p is a core point, then it forms a *cluster* together with all points (core or non-core) that are reachable from it.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Each cluster contains at least one core point; non-core points can be part of a cluster, but they form its "edge", since they cannot be used to reach more points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Reachability is not a symmetric relation: by definition, only core points can reach non-core points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The opposite is not true, so a non-core point may be reachable, but nothing can be reached from it.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Therefore, a further notion of *connectedness* is needed to formally define the extent of the clusters found by DBSCAN.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Two points p and q are density-connected if there is a point o such that both p and q are reachable from o.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] If a point is density-reachable from some point of the cluster, it is part of the cluster as well.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN requires two parameters: ε (eps) and the minimum number of points required to form a dense region (minPts).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] It starts with an arbitrary starting point that has not been visited.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] This point's ε-neighborhood is retrieved, and if it contains sufficiently many points, a cluster is started.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Otherwise, the point is labeled as noise.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Note that this point might later be found in a sufficiently sized ε-environment of a different point and hence be made part of a cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] If a point is found to be a dense part of a cluster, its ε-neighborhood is also part of that cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Hence, all points that are found within the ε-neighborhood are added, as is their own ε-neighborhood when they are also dense.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] This process continues until the density-connected cluster is completely found.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Then, a new unvisited point is retrieved and processed, leading to the discovery of a further cluster or noise.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN can be used with any distance function (as well as similarity functions or other predicates).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The distance function (dist) can therefore be seen as an additional parameter.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Find the connected components of *core* points on the neighbor graph, ignoring all non-core points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Assign each non-core point to a nearby cluster if the cluster is an ε (eps) neighbor, otherwise assign it to noise.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] A naive implementation of this requires storing the neighborhoods in step 1, thus requiring substantial memory.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The original DBSCAN algorithm does not require this by performing these steps for one point at a time.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] where $d_{db}(p,q)$ gives the smallest $\varepsilon$ such that two points p and q are density-connected.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN visits each point of the database, possibly multiple times (e.g., as candidates to different clusters).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] For practical considerations, however, the time complexity is mostly governed by the number of regionQuery invocations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Without the use of an accelerating index structure, or on degenerated data (e.g. all points within a distance less than ε), the worst case run time complexity remains O(*n*²).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The $\textstyle {\binom {n}{2}}$ - *n* = (*n*²-*n*)/2-sized upper triangle of the distance matrix can be materialized to avoid distance recomputations, but this needs O(*n*²) memory, whereas a non-matrix based implementation of DBSCAN only needs O(*n*) memory.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN can find arbitrarily-shaped clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] It can even find a cluster completely surrounded by (but not connected to) a different cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Due to the MinPts parameter, the so-called single-link effect (different clusters being connected by a thin line of points) is reduced.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN has a notion of noise, and is robust to outliers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN requires just two parameters and is mostly insensitive to the ordering of the points in the database.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN is designed for use with databases that can accelerate region queries, e.g. using an R* tree.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The parameters minPts and ε can be set by a domain expert, if the data is well understood.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The quality of DBSCAN depends on the distance measure used in the function regionQuery(P,ε).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The most common distance metric used is Euclidean distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Especially for high-dimensional data, this metric can be rendered almost useless due to the so-called "Curse of dimensionality", making it difficult to find an appropriate value for ε.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] This effect, however, is also present in any other algorithm based on Euclidean distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN cannot cluster data sets well with large differences in densities, since the minPts-ε combination cannot then be chosen appropriately for all clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] If the data and scale are not well understood, choosing a meaningful distance threshold ε can be difficult.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] See the section below on extensions for algorithmic modifications to handle these issues.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Every data mining task has the problem of parameters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Every parameter influences the algorithm in specific ways.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] For DBSCAN, the parameters ε and *minPts* are needed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The parameters must be specified by the user.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Ideally, the value of ε is given by the problem to solve (e.g. a physical distance), and *minPts* is then the desired minimum cluster size.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] OPTICS can be seen as a generalization of DBSCAN that replaces the ε parameter with a maximum value that mostly affects performance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] *MinPts* then essentially becomes the minimum cluster size to find.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] While the algorithm is much easier to parameterize than DBSCAN, the results are a bit more difficult to use, as it will usually produce a hierarchical clustering instead of the simple data partitioning that DBSCAN produces.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Recently, one of the original authors of DBSCAN has revisited DBSCAN and OPTICS, and published a refined version of hierarchical DBSCAN (HDBSCAN*), which no longer has the notion of border points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Instead, only the core points form the cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] A spectral implementation of DBSCAN is related to spectral clustering in the trivial case of determining connected graph components — the optimal clusters with no edges cut.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] However, it can be computationally intensive, up to $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Additionally, one has to choose the number of eigenvectors to compute.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] For performance reasons, the original DBSCAN algorithm remains preferable to its spectral implementation.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Generalized DBSCAN (GDBSCAN) is a generalization by the same authors to arbitrary "neighborhood" and "dense" predicates.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The ε and *minPts* parameters are removed from the original algorithm and moved to the predicates.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] For example, on polygon data, the "neighborhood" could be any intersecting polygon, whereas the density predicate uses the polygon areas instead of just the object count.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Various extensions to the DBSCAN algorithm have been proposed, including methods for parallelization, parameter estimation, and support for uncertain data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The basic idea has been extended to hierarchical clustering by the OPTICS algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] DBSCAN is also used as part of subspace clustering algorithms like PreDeCon and SUBCLU.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] HDBSCAN* is a hierarchical version of DBSCAN which is also faster than OPTICS, from which a flat partition consisting of the most prominent clusters can be extracted from the hierarchy.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] Different implementations of the same algorithm were found to exhibit enormous performance differences, with the fastest on a test data set finishing in 1.4 seconds, the slowest taking 13803 seconds.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/dbscan] The differences can be attributed to implementation quality, language and compiler differences, and the use of indexes for acceleration.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Determining the number of clusters in a data set, a quantity often labelled *k* as in the *k*-means algorithm, is a frequent problem in data clustering, and is a distinct issue from the process of actually solving the clustering problem.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] For a certain class of clustering algorithms (in particular *k*-means, *k*-medoids and expectation–maximization algorithm), there is a parameter commonly referred to as *k* that specifies the number of clusters to detect.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Other algorithms such as DBSCAN and OPTICS algorithm do not require the specification of this parameter; hierarchical clustering avoids the problem altogether.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The correct choice of *k* is often ambiguous, with interpretations depending on the shape and scale of the distribution of points in a data set and the desired clustering resolution of the user.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] In addition, increasing *k* without penalty will always reduce the amount of error in the resulting clustering, to the extreme case of zero error if each data point is considered its own cluster (i.e., when *k* equals the number of data points, *n*).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Intuitively then, *the optimal choice of*k*will strike a balance between maximum compression of the data using a single cluster, and maximum accuracy by assigning each data point to its own cluster*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] If an appropriate value of *k* is not apparent from prior knowledge of the properties of the data set, it must be chosen somehow.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] There are several categories of methods for making this decision.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The elbow method looks at the percentage of explained variance as a function of the number of clusters: One should choose a number of clusters so that adding another cluster does not give much better modeling of the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] More precisely, if one plots the percentage of variance explained by the clusters against the number of clusters, the first clusters will add much information (explain a lot of variance), but at some point the marginal gain will drop, giving an angle in the graph.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The number of clusters is chosen at this point, hence the "elbow criterion".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] In most datasets, this "elbow" is ambiguous, making this method subjective and unreliable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Because the scale of the axes is arbitrary, the concept of an angle is not well-defined, and even on uniform random data, the curve produces an "elbow", making the method rather unreliable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Percentage of variance explained is the ratio of the between-group variance to the total variance, also known as an F-test.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] A slight variation of this method plots the curvature of the within group variance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The method can be traced to speculation by Robert L.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] While the idea of the elbow method sounds simple and straightforward, other methods (as detailed below) give better results.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Another set of methods for determining the number of clusters are information criteria, such as the Akaike information criterion (AIC), Bayesian information criterion (BIC), or the deviance information criterion (DIC) — if it is possible to make a likelihood function for the clustering model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] For example: The *k*-means model is "almost" a Gaussian mixture model and one can construct a likelihood for the Gaussian mixture model and thus also determine information criterion values.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Rate distortion theory has been applied to choosing *k* called the "jump" method, which determines the number of clusters that maximizes efficiency while minimizing error by information-theoretic standards.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The strategy of the algorithm is to generate a distortion curve for the input data by running a standard clustering algorithm such as k-means for all values of *k* between 1 and *n*, and computing the distortion (described below) of the resulting clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The distortion curve is then transformed by a negative power chosen based on the dimensionality of the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Jumps in the resulting values then signify reasonable choices for *k*, with the largest jump representing the best choice.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The distortion of a clustering of some input data is formally defined as follows: Let the data set be modeled as a *p*-dimensional random variable, *X*, consisting of a mixture distribution of *G* components with common covariance, Γ.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] This is also the average Mahalanobis distance per dimension between *X* and the closest cluster center $c_{X}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Because the minimization over all possible sets of cluster centers is prohibitively complex, the distortion is computed in practice by generating a set of cluster centers using a standard clustering algorithm and computing the distortion using the result.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The choice of the transform power $Y=(p/2)$ is motivated by asymptotic reasoning using results from rate distortion theory.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Let the data *X* have a single, arbitrarily *p*-dimensional Gaussian distribution, and let fixed $K=\lfloor \alpha ^{p}\rfloor$ , for some α greater than zero.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Then the distortion of a clustering of *K* clusters in the limit as *p* goes to infinity is $\alpha ^{-2}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] It can be seen that asymptotically, the distortion of a clustering to the power $(-p/2)$ is proportional to $\alpha ^{p}$ , which by definition is approximately the number of clusters *K*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] In other words, for a single Gaussian distribution, increasing *K* beyond the true number of clusters, which should be one, causes a linear growth in distortion.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] This behavior is important in the general case of a mixture of multiple distribution components.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Let *X* be a mixture of *G* *p*-dimensional Gaussian distributions with common covariance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Then for any fixed *K* less than *G*, the distortion of a clustering as *p* goes to infinity is infinite.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Intuitively, this means that a clustering of less than the correct number of clusters is unable to describe asymptotically high-dimensional data, causing the distortion to increase without limit.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] If, as described above, *K* is made an increasing function of *p*, namely, $K=\lfloor \alpha ^{p}\rfloor$ , the same result as above is achieved, with the value of the distortion in the limit as *p* goes to infinity being equal to $\alpha ^{-2}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Correspondingly, there is the same proportional relationship between the transformed distortion and the number of clusters, *K*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Putting the results above together, it can be seen that for sufficiently high values of *p*, the transformed distortion $d_{K}^{-p/2}$ is approximately zero for *K* < *G*, then jumps suddenly and begins increasing linearly for *K* ≥ *G*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The jump algorithm for choosing *K* makes use of these behaviors to identify the most likely value for the true number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Although the mathematical support for the method is given in terms of asymptotic results, the algorithm has been empirically verified to work well in a variety of data sets with reasonable dimensionality.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] In addition to the localized jump method described above, there exists a second algorithm for choosing *K* using the same transformed distortion values known as the broken line method.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The broken line method is more robust than the jump method in that its decision is global rather than local, but it also relies on the assumption of Gaussian mixture components, whereas the jump method is fully non-parametric and has been shown to be viable for general mixture distributions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The average silhouette of the data is another useful criterion for assessing the natural number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The silhouette of a data instance is a measure of how closely it is matched to data within its cluster and how loosely it is matched to data of the neighboring cluster, i.e., the cluster whose average distance from the datum is lowest.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] A silhouette close to 1 implies the datum is in an appropriate cluster, while a silhouette close to −1 implies the datum is in the wrong cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Optimization techniques such as genetic algorithms are useful in determining the number of clusters that gives rise to the largest silhouette.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] It is also possible to re-scale the data in such a way that the silhouette is more likely to be maximized at the correct number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] One can also use the process of cross-validation to analyze the number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] In this process, the data is partitioned into *v* parts.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Each of the parts is then set aside at turn as a test set, a clustering model computed on the other *v* − 1 training sets, and the value of the objective function (for example, the sum of the squared distances to the centroids for *k*-means) calculated for the test set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] These *v* values are calculated and averaged for each alternative number of clusters, and the cluster number selected such that further increase in number of clusters leads to only a small reduction in the objective function.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Note that in D each row and each column must contain at least one non-zero element.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Kernel matrix defines the proximity of the input information.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] For example, in Gaussian radial basis function, it determines the dot product of the inputs in a higher-dimensional space, called feature space.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] It is believed that the data become more linearly separable in the feature space, and hence, linear algorithms can be applied on the data with a higher success.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The kernel matrix can thus be analyzed in order to find the optimal number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The method proceeds by the eigenvalue decomposition of the kernel matrix.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] It will then analyze the eigenvalues and eigenvectors to obtain a measure of the compactness of the input distribution.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Finally, a plot will be drawn, where the elbow of that plot indicates the optimal number of clusters in the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Unlike previous methods, this technique does not need to perform any clustering a-priori.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] It directly finds the number of clusters from the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Robert Tibshirani, Guenther Walther, and Trevor Hastie proposed estimating the number of clusters in a data set via the gap statistic.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The gap statistics, based on theoretical grounds, measures how far is the pooled within-cluster sum of squares around the cluster centers from the sum of squares expected under the null reference distribution of data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The expected value is estimated by simulating null reference data of characteristics of the original data, but lacking any clusters in it.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The optimal number of clusters is then estimated as the value of *k* for which the observed sum of squares falls farthest below the null reference.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] Unlike many previous methods, the gap statistics can tell us that there is no value of *k* for which there is a good clustering, but the reliability depends on how plausible the assumed null distribution (e.g., a uniform distribution) is on the given data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] This tends to work well in synthetic settings, but cannot handle difficult data sets with, e.g., uninformative attributes well because it assumes all attributes to be equally important.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/determining-the-number-of-clusters-in-a-data-set] The gap statistics is implemented as the *clusGap* function in the *cluster* package in R.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In data mining and statistics, **hierarchical clustering** (also called **hierarchical cluster analysis** or **HCA**) is a method of cluster analysis that seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In general, the merges and splits are determined in a greedy manner.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The results of hierarchical clustering are usually presented in a dendrogram.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Hierarchical clustering has the distinct advantage that any valid measure of distance can be used.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In fact, the observations themselves are not required: all that is used is a matrix of distances.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] On the other hand, except for the special case of single-linkage distance, none of the algorithms (except exhaustive search in ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ ) can be guaranteed to find the optimum solution.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The standard algorithm for **hierarchical agglomerative clustering** (HAC) has a time complexity of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ and requires $\Omega (n^{2})$ memory, which makes it too slow for even medium data sets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] However, for some special cases, optimal efficient agglomerative methods (of complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known: **SLINK** for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] With a heap, the runtime of the general case can be reduced to ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ , at the cost of additional the memory requirements.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In many cases, the memory overheads of this approach are too large to make it practically usable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Methods exist which use quadtrees that demonstrate ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ total running time with ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ space.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Divisive clustering with an exhaustive search is ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n})$ , but it is common to use faster heuristics to choose splits, such as *k*-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] While the linkage criterion determines how dissimilarity between sets of observations is computed, the underlying distance metric determines how dissimilarity between individual observations is measured.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering permits any valid measure of distance, the choice of metric is guided by the nature of the data and can have a significant effect on the resulting clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] It is often preferred when features are measured on different scales or when the data contain outliers, as it is less sensitive to large deviations than Euclidean distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because it disregards vector magnitude, it is frequently used in text mining and document clustering, where documents are represented as high-dimensional term-frequency vectors.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike Euclidean distance, it is scale-invariant and is useful when features are correlated or measured in different units.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric interacts with the choice of linkage criterion.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] For example, Ward's method and centroid-based linkages are defined in terms of squared Euclidean distances, whereas single-linkage and complete-linkage clustering can be used with any valid metric.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In order to decide which clusters should be combined (for agglomerative), or where a cluster should be split (for divisive), a measure of dissimilarity between sets of observations is required.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of metric as well as linkage can have a major impact on the result of the clustering, where the lower level metric determines which objects are most similar, whereas the linkage criterion influences the shape of the clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] For example, complete-linkage tends to produce more spherical clusters than single-linkage.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The linkage criterion determines the distance between sets of observations as a function of the pairwise distances between observations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Some of these can only be recomputed recursively (WPGMA, WPGMC), for many a recursive computation with Lance-Williams-equations is more efficient, while for other (Hausdorff, Medoid) the distances have to be computed with the slower full formula.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of linkage criterion significantly affects the shape and quality of the resulting clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Each method has distinct strengths and weaknesses depending on the structure of the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The naive implementation of agglomerative hierarchical clustering has a time complexity of O(*n*³) and a space complexity of O(*n*²), where *n* is the number of data points, because at each of the *n* − 1 merge steps the algorithm must search and update an *n* × *n* proximity matrix.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] For single linkage, optimized algorithms based on minimum spanning trees reduce the time complexity to O(*n*² log *n*).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] For other linkage criteria, the use of priority queues and nearest-neighbor chains can also achieve O(*n*² log *n*) time in practice.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Hausdorff linkage is a hierarchical clustering criterion based on the Hausdorff distance, a metric defined between sets of points in a given metric space.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Unlike standard linkage methods that rely on pairwise distances between individual observations, Hausdorff linkage evaluates distances between entire clusters, thereby incorporating information about their geometric structure.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Formally, let $(S,\delta )$ be a metric space, and let A and B be nonempty compact subsets of S .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This definition captures the largest distance from a point in one set to the closest point in the other set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Equivalently, it can be interpreted as the smallest radius r such that every point of A lies within distance r of some point in B , and every point of B lies within distance r of some point in A .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In this sense, the Hausdorff distance measures the maximum mismatch between two sets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, Hausdorff linkage uses $d_{H}(A,B)$ as the dissimilarity measure between clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, each data point forms its own cluster, and the Hausdorff distance between singleton sets reduces to the original metric.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest Hausdorff distance are merged, and distances are recomputed using the same set-based definition.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This iterative process continues until all points belong to a single cluster, producing a hierarchical structure (dendrogram).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Compared to other linkage criteria such as single, complete, or average linkage, Hausdorff linkage operates on a set-to-set basis rather than relying solely on pairwise point distances.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] As a result, it captures the global geometry of clusters and can better preserve structural features of the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] It has been shown to provide behavior intermediate between single and complete linkage, avoiding the chaining effect of the former while reducing the tendency of the latter to overestimate distances between clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] However, these advantages come with increased computational cost.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Computing the Hausdorff distance between two clusters typically requires evaluating distances between all pairs of points across the sets, often via a max–min procedure over a distance matrix.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This makes Hausdorff linkage more computationally expensive than simpler linkage criteria, particularly for large datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Overall, Hausdorff linkage provides a mathematically well-founded clustering approach that is effective for distinguishing complex structures in data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] For example, suppose this data is to be clustered, and the Euclidean distance is the distance metric.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the tree at a given height will give a partitioning clustering at a selected precision.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In this example, cutting after the second row (from the top) of the dendrogram will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e} {f}.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting after the third row will yield clusters {a} {b c} {d e f}, which is a coarser clustering, with a smaller number but larger clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The clustering process can also be illustrated step-by-step to show how the dendrogram is constructed from the underlying data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In this visualization, each point begins as its own cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] At each step, the two clusters with the smallest distance between them are merged.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] On the left, dashed lines indicate which clusters are combined, and a running list of cluster groupings shows how clusters evolve over time.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] On the right, the dendrogram is constructed simultaneously, with each merge represented by a new branch.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The height of each merge in the dendrogram corresponds to the distance or dissimilarity between the clusters being combined.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Merges that occur at lower heights represent clusters that are more similar, while merges at higher heights indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Color-coding is used to associate each merge step in the data visualization with its corresponding branch in the dendrogram.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] A key aspect of interpreting a dendrogram is understanding the meaning of branch height.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The height at which two clusters are joined represents the distance or dissimilarity between those clusters, where lower merges indicate greater similarity and higher merges indicate greater dissimilarity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Early merges at lower heights reflect the closest relationships between observations, while later merges combine increasingly different groups.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] When the dendrogram is scaled using actual or normalized distances, the vertical spacing between merges provides insight into the relative differences between clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Large vertical gaps between successive merges often indicate meaningful separations in the data.and can help guide the selection of cluster boundaries, although dendrograms alone should not be used to definitively determine the number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because dendrograms summarize underlying distance relationships, some information may be lost in the visualization, and interpretations are generally most reliable for clusters that merge at lower heights.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In hierarchical clustering, the number of clusters is not determined automatically and must be chosen by analyzing the dendrogram.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] A common approach is to “cut” the dendrogram at a selected height, which partitions the data into clusters based on where the cut intersects the tree structure.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The choice of cut level has a significant impact on the resulting clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] One widely used heuristic is to identify large vertical gaps in the dendrogram, which correspond to substantial increases in the distance between successive merges.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Cutting the dendrogram at a height just before such a gap can produce clusters that reflect natural groupings in the data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This is based on the observation that merges occurring at much larger distances often combine dissimilar clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In practice, the selection of the number of clusters may also depend on domain knowledge or application-specific requirements.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Quantitative measures such as the silhouette coefficient can be used to evaluate the quality of different clusterings.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because hierarchical clustering is sensitive to the choice of distance metric and linkage criterion, the optimal number of clusters may vary depending on these factors.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This method builds the hierarchy from the individual elements by progressively merging clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In our example, we have six elements {a} {b} {c} {d} {e} and {f}.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The first step is to determine which elements to merge in a cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Usually, we want to take the two closest elements, according to the chosen distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Optionally, one can also construct a distance matrix at this stage, where the number in the *i*-th row *j*-th column is the distance between the *i*-th and *j*-th elements.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Then, as clustering progresses, rows and columns are merged as the clusters are merged and the distances updated.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This is a common way to implement this type of clustering, and has the benefit of caching distances between clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] A simple agglomerative clustering algorithm is described in the single-linkage clustering page; it can easily be adapted to different types of linkage (see below).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Suppose we have merged the two closest elements *b* and *c*, we now have the following clusters {*a*}, {*b*, *c*}, {*d*}, {*e*} and {*f*}, and want to merge them further.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] To do that, we need to take the distance between {a} and {b c}, and therefore define the distance between two clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In case of tied minimum distances, a pair is randomly chosen, thus being able to generate several structurally different dendrograms.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Alternatively, all tied pairs may be joined at the same time, generating a unique dendrogram.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] One can always decide to stop clustering when there is a sufficiently small number of clusters (number criterion).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Some linkages may also guarantee that agglomeration occurs at a greater distance between clusters than the previous agglomeration, and then one can stop clustering when the clusters are too far apart to be merged (distance criterion).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] However, this is not the case of, e.g., the centroid linkage where the so-called reversals (inversions, departures from ultrametricity) may occur.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The basic principle of divisive clustering was published as the DIANA (DIvisive ANAlysis clustering) algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Initially, all data is in the same cluster, and the largest cluster is split until every object is separate.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because there exist $O(2^{n})$ ways of splitting each cluster, heuristics are needed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] DIANA chooses the object with the maximum average dissimilarity and then moves all objects to this cluster that are more similar to the new cluster than to the remainder.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Informally, DIANA is not so much a process of "dividing" as it is of "hollowing out": each iteration, an existing cluster (e.g. the initial cluster of the entire dataset) is chosen to form a new cluster inside of it.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Objects progressively move to this nested cluster, and hollow out the existing cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Eventually, all that's left inside a cluster is nested clusters that grew there, without it owning any loose objects by itself.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] As long as $C_{*}$ isn't empty, keep migrating objects from $C_{*}$ to add them to $C_{\textrm {new}}$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Intuitively, $D(i)$ above measures how strongly an object wants to leave its current cluster, but it is attenuated when the object wouldn't fit in the splinter group either.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Such objects will likely start their own splinter group eventually.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The dendrogram of DIANA can be constructed by letting the splinter group $C_{\textrm {new}}$ be a child of the hollowed-out cluster $C_{*}$ each time.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This constructs a tree with $C_{0}$ as its root and n unique single-object clusters as its leaves.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Standard hierarchical agglomerative clustering is difficult to apply to very large datasets because typical implementations require substantial memory for pairwise structures and can scale poorly as n grows (see § Complexity above).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] In computational biology, single-cell technologies such as mass cytometry routinely produce tens of millions of high-dimensional observations, which motivates specialized workflows that preserve biological resolution without requiring that every expensive step be run on the full matrix at once.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The figure summarizes the HAL-x workflow: dimensionality reduction for density estimation, density-based seed clusters, a supervised linkage graph between clusters, and successive merges to a chosen generalization threshold.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] This design targets scalability: expensive steps are deliberately restricted to manageable downscaled subsamples, while label prediction can be applied broadly to the full dataset once the hierarchy and classifiers are established.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] Because of this, HAL-x is extremely useful when hierarchical clustering requires minimal RAM.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] A practical limitation, common to embedding-first pipelines, is that low-dimensional representations can distort global geometry and reduce accuracy.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The HAL-x paper discusses when auxiliary preprocessing such as PCA may help for correlated features.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] HAL-x was motivated by workflows in which biologists need many related clusterings at different granularities (for example to preserve rare leukocyte subsets while still summarizing abundant lineages) without repeatedly training separate models from scratch on millions of cells.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/hierarchical-clustering] The authors report analyses on large cytometry-style datasets where rapid, tunable clusterings are used to support downstream interpretation of cellular phenotypes across conditions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The problem is computationally difficult (NP-hard); however, efficient heuristic algorithms converge quickly to a local optimum.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] These are usually similar to the expectation–maximization algorithm for mixtures of Gaussian distributions via an iterative refinement approach employed by both *k-means* and *Gaussian mixture modeling*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] They both use cluster centers to model the data; however, *k*-means clustering tends to find clusters of comparable spatial extent, while the Gaussian mixture model allows clusters to have different shapes.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The unsupervised *k*-means algorithm has a loose relationship to the *k*-nearest neighbor classifier, a popular supervised machine learning technique for classification that is often confused with *k*-means due to the name.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Applying the 1-nearest neighbor classifier to the cluster centers obtained by *k*-means classifies new data into the existing clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This is known as nearest centroid classifier or Rocchio algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Since the total variance is constant, this is equivalent to maximizing the sum of squared deviations between points in *different* clusters (between-cluster sum of squares, BCSS).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This deterministic relationship is also related to the law of total variance in probability theory.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The term "*k*-means" was first used by James MacQueen in 1967, though the idea goes back to Hugo Steinhaus in 1956.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The standard algorithm was first proposed by Stuart Lloyd of Bell Labs in 1957 as a technique for pulse-code modulation, although it was not published as a journal article until 1982.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Forgy published essentially the same method, which is why it is sometimes referred to as the Lloyd–Forgy algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Early applications of the k-means algorithm were primarily found in signal processing and data compression, particularly in the context of vector quantization.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's work at Bell Labs focused on representing analog signals using a limited set of discrete values, where clustering was used to reduce the amount of data required while preserving signal quality.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] As computing power increased, k-means clustering became widely used in pattern recognition and statistical classification due to its simplicity and computational efficiency.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It was later adopted in early machine learning and data analysis tasks involving large datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Despite its widespread use, limitations such as sensitivity to initial centroid placement and difficulty handling non-spherical clusters were recognized early on, motivating the development of improved clustering methods and initialization techniques.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The most common algorithm uses an iterative refinement technique.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Due to its ubiquity, it is often called "the *k*-means algorithm"; it is also referred to as Lloyd's algorithm, particularly in the computer science community.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It is sometimes also referred to as "naïve *k*-means", because there exist much faster alternatives.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] **Update step**: Recalculate means (centroids) for observations assigned to each cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The objective function in *k*-means is the WCSS (within cluster sum of squares).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] After each iteration, the WCSS monotonically decreases, giving a nonnegative monotonically decreasing sequence.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This guarantees that the *k*-means always converges, but not necessarily to the global optimum.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm has converged when the assignments no longer change or equivalently, when the WCSS has become stable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm is not guaranteed to find the optimal cluster assignment.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm is often presented as assigning objects to the nearest cluster by distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Using a different distance function other than (squared) Euclidean distance may prevent the algorithm from converging.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Various modifications of *k*-means such as spherical *k*-means and *k*-medoids have been proposed to allow using other distance measures.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The below pseudocode outlines the implementation of the standard *k*-means clustering algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Initialization of centroids, distance metric between points and centroids, and the calculation of new centroids are design choices and will vary with different implementations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In this example pseudocode, `distance()` returns the distance between the specified points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Commonly used initialization methods are Forgy and Random Partition.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The Forgy method randomly chooses *k* observations from the dataset and uses these as the initial means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The Random Partition method first randomly assigns a cluster to each observation and then proceeds to the update step, thus computing the initial mean to be the centroid of the cluster's randomly assigned points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The Forgy method tends to spread the initial means out, while Random Partition places all of them close to the center of the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] According to Hamerly et al., the Random Partition method is generally preferable for algorithms such as the *k*-harmonic means and fuzzy *k*-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For expectation maximization and standard *k*-means algorithms, the Forgy method of initialization is preferable.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] A comprehensive study by Celebi et al., however, found that popular initialization methods such as Forgy, Random Partition, and Maximin often perform poorly, whereas Bradley and Fayyad's approach performs "consistently" in "the best group" and *k*-means++ performs "generally well".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm does not guarantee convergence to the global optimum.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The result may depend on the initial clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] As the algorithm is usually fast, it is common to run it multiple times with different starting conditions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] However, worst-case performance can be slow: in particular certain point sets, even in two dimensions, converge in exponential time, that is 2Ω(*n*).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] These point sets do not seem to arise in practice: this is corroborated by the fact that the smoothed running time of *k*-means is polynomial.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The "assignment" step is referred to as the "expectation step", while the "update step" is a maximization step, making this algorithm a variant of the *generalized* expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Thus, a variety of heuristic algorithms such as Lloyd's algorithm given above are generally used.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] On data that does have a clustering structure, the number of iterations until convergence is often small, and results only improve slightly after the first dozen iterations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's algorithm is therefore often considered to be of "linear" complexity in practice, although it is in the worst case superpolynomial when performed until convergence.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Lloyd's algorithm is the standard approach for this problem.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] However, it spends a lot of processing time computing the distances between each of the *k* cluster centers and the *n* data points.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Since points usually stay in the same clusters after a few iterations, much of this work is unnecessary, making the naïve implementation very inefficient.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Some implementations use caching and the triangle inequality in order to create bounds and accelerate Lloyd's algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Finding the optimal number of clusters (*k*) for *k*-means clustering is a crucial step to ensure that the clustering results are meaningful and useful.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Several techniques are available to determine a suitable number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Hartigan and Wong's method provides a variation of *k*-means algorithm which progresses towards a local minimum of the minimum sum-of-squares problem with different solution updates.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The method is a local search that iteratively attempts to relocate a sample into a different cluster as long as this process improves the objective function.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] When no sample can be relocated into a different cluster with an improvement of the objective, the method stops (in a local minimum).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In a similar way as the classical *k*-means, the approach remains a heuristic since it does not necessarily guarantee that the final solution is globally optimum.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Let $\varphi (S_{j})$ be the individual cost of $S_{j}$ defined by ${\textstyle \sum _{x\in S_{j}}(x-\mu _{j})^{2}}$ , with $\mu _{j}$ the center of the cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Different move acceptance strategies can be used.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In a *first-improvement* strategy, any improving relocation can be applied, whereas in a *best-improvement* strategy, all possible relocations are iteratively tested and only the best is applied at each iteration.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The former approach favors speed, whether the latter approach generally favors solution quality at the expense of additional computational time.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Initialization and restart techniques discussed in the previous sections are one alternative to find better solutions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] More recently, global optimization algorithms based on branch-and-bound and semidefinite programming have produced ‘’provenly optimal’’ solutions for datasets with up to 4,177 entities and 20,531 features.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] As expected, due to the NP-hardness of the subjacent optimization problem, the computational time of optimal algorithms for *k*-means quickly increases beyond this size.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Optimal solutions for small- and medium-scale still remain valuable as a benchmark tool, to evaluate the quality of other heuristics.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It is indeed known that finding better local minima of the minimum sum-of-squares clustering problem can make the difference between failure and success to recover cluster structures in feature spaces of high dimension.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] A key limitation of *k*-means is its cluster model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The concept is based on spherical clusters that are separable so that the mean converges towards the cluster center.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The clusters are expected to be of similar size, so that the assignment to the nearest cluster center is the correct assignment.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] When for example applying *k*-means with a value of $k=3$ onto the well-known Iris flower data set, the result often fails to separate the three Iris species contained in the data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] With $k=2$ , the two visible clusters (one containing two species) will be discovered, whereas with $k=3$ one of the two clusters will be split into two even parts.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In fact, $k=2$ is more appropriate for this data set, despite the data set's containing 3 *classes*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] As with any other clustering algorithm, the *k*-means result makes assumptions that the data satisfy certain criteria.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It works well on some data sets, and fails on others.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The result of *k*-means can be seen as the Voronoi cells of the cluster means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Since data is split halfway between cluster means, this can lead to suboptimal splits as can be seen in the "mouse" example.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The Gaussian models used by the expectation–maximization algorithm (arguably a generalization of *k*-means) are more flexible by having both variances and covariances.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The EM result is thus able to accommodate clusters of variable size much better than *k*-means as well as correlated clusters (not in this example).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In counterpart, EM requires the optimization of a larger number of free parameters and poses some methodological issues due to vanishing clusters or badly-conditioned covariance matrices.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] *k*-means is closely related to nonparametric Bayesian modeling.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In biological applications, the limitations of standard *k*-means clustering are often addressed by adapting the distance measures used and objective functions to better reflect the structure of experimental data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Rather than relying on Euclidean distance and variance-based measures of cluster scatter, alternative similarity metrics such as the Jaccard index are sometimes used when analyzing genomic datasets with k-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In these contexts, clustering may be performed directly on distance matrices, and medoids (representative data points that have the smallest average distance to every other point within a cluster) may be selected as cluster centers instead of arithmetic means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This allows clustering methods to capture patterns of shared genomic features or co-occurrence that are not well represented in a traditional Euclidean analysis.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Clustering is widely used in biological data analysis to identify patterns in high-dimensional datasets such as gene expression profiles and genomic interaction matrices.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Techniques such as *k*-means clustering partition observations into groups based on similarity, allowing researchers to detect structure in complex datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In gene expression studies, clustering is commonly used to group genes with similar expression profiles, often revealing co-regulated genes and underlying biological interactions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In addition to gene expression analysis, clustering approaches are applied to chromatin interaction data to identify regions of coordinated activity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Similarity measures such as the Jaccard index can be used to quantify shared features between observations, and clustering of the resulting distance matrices can reveal structural organization within the genome.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] These patterns are commonly visualized using heatmaps, where clustered regions correspond to domains of interaction or co-segregation, providing insight into the regulatory organization of the genome.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In such analyses, clustering of similarity or co-detection matrices can reveal groups of genomic windows that exhibit coordinated behavior across experimental conditions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Clustering methods provide a practical method for uncovering biologically meaningful structure from complex datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] By grouping observations with similar patterns of genomic detection, expression, or interaction, these techniques can reveal functional relationships, spatial organization within the nucleus, and regulatory behavior.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In many applications, the resulting clusters correspond to distinct biological states or structural domains, further illustrating the broad applicability of k-means clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Vector quantization, a technique commonly used in signal processing and computer graphics, involves reducing the color palette of an image to a fixed number of colors, known as *k*.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] One popular method for achieving vector quantization is through *k*-means clustering.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In this process, *k*-means is applied to the color space of an image to partition it into k clusters, with each cluster representing a distinct color in the image.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This technique is particularly useful in image segmentation tasks, where it helps identify and group similar colors together.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Example: In the field of computer graphics, *k*-means clustering is often employed for color quantization in image compression.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] By reducing the number of colors used to represent an image, file sizes can be significantly reduced without significant loss of visual quality.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For instance, consider an image with millions of colors.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] By applying *k*-means clustering with *k* set to a smaller number, the image can be represented using a more limited color palette, resulting in a compressed version that consumes less storage space and bandwidth.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Other uses of vector quantization include non-random sampling, as *k*-means can easily be used to choose *k* different but prototypical objects from a large data set for further analysis.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Cluster analysis, a fundamental task in data mining and machine learning, involves grouping a set of data points into clusters based on their similarity.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] *k*-means clustering is a popular algorithm used for partitioning data into k clusters, where each cluster is represented by its centroid.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] However, the pure *k*-means algorithm is not very flexible, and as such is of limited use (except for when vector quantization as above is actually the desired use case).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In particular, the parameter *k* is known to be hard to choose (as discussed above) when not given by external constraints.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Another limitation is that it cannot be used with arbitrary distance functions or on non-numerical data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For these use cases, many other algorithms are superior.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Example: In marketing, *k*-means clustering is frequently employed for market segmentation, where customers with similar characteristics or behaviors are grouped together.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For instance, a retail company may use *k*-means clustering to segment its customer base into distinct groups based on factors such as purchasing behavior, demographics, and geographic location.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] These customer segments can then be targeted with tailored marketing strategies and product offerings to maximize sales and customer satisfaction.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This use of *k*-means has been successfully combined with simple, linear classifiers for semi-supervised learning in NLP (specifically for named-entity recognition) and in computer vision.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] On an object recognition task, it was found to exhibit comparable performance with more sophisticated feature learning approaches such as autoencoders and restricted Boltzmann machines.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] However, it generally requires more data, for equivalent performance, because each data point only contributes to one "feature".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Example: In natural language processing (NLP), *k*-means clustering has been integrated with simple linear classifiers for semi-supervised learning tasks such as named-entity recognition (NER).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] By first clustering unlabeled text data using *k*-means, meaningful features can be extracted to improve the performance of NER models.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For instance, *k*-means clustering can be applied to identify clusters of words or phrases that frequently co-occur in the input text, which can then be used as features for training the NER model.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This approach has been shown to achieve comparable performance with more complex feature learning techniques such as autoencoders and restricted Boltzmann machines, albeit with a greater requirement for labeled data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Standard Lloyd’s algorithm is inherently sequential.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It has an effective time complexity of O(nkdi), which becomes a bottleneck as the number of data points (n) or dimensions (d) increases.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This can be inefficient when used with massive, multidimensional data sets like social networks.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Various parallelization strategies have been developed to distribute the workload across multi-core processors, GPUs, and distributed clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] We see that in both parallel versions; efficiency is greatly increased for large datasets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This speedup is significant in the OpenACC implementation, due to the massively parallel nature of GPU architectures.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Modern astronomical surveys like APOGEE and the Gaia catalog collect spectroscopic and photometric data for millions of stars, making manual classification impractical at scale.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] *K*-means clustering has been applied to this data to automatically identify distinct stellar populations based on properties like luminosity, temperature, color, and chemical abundance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] One major application is identifying stellar populations through chemical tagging.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Stars that form together in the same cluster share similar chemical compositions, so clustering algorithms applied to abundance data can recover these groupings even after the stars have spread throughout the galaxy.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Studies using *k*-means on APOGEE infrared spectra measured abundances of up to 13 elements and successfully distinguished known star clusters from surrounding field stars.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This has also revealed populations with unusual abundance patterns that would be difficult to catch through manual inspection.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Proper initialization is very important when it comes to finding global optimum in a clustering algorithm.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Random initialization is often used for k means clustering, but this can result in poor cluster quality.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This is why the k-means++ initialization algorithm was developed.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm attempts to find initial centers that are as close to possible to the global optimum, reducing computing time and producing more accurate clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The k-means++ algorithm works by spreading out the initial cluster centers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It selects the first center uniformly at random from the dataset.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Each subsequent center is chosen stochastically, with the probability of a point being selected proportional to its contribution to the overall error.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This method achieves an O(log k) approximation of the optimum solution.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The primary drawback of standard k-means++ is its inherent sequential nature.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] To find k initial centers, the algorithm must make k separate passes over the data, as the selection of each new center depends on the previous choices.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This becomes prohibitively slow when clustering massive datasets into a large number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] To overcome these limitations, researchers developed k-means||, a parallel version of k-means++.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Instead of sampling a single point per pass, k-means|| uses an oversampling factor ℓ = Ω (k) to sample multiple points in each round.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The algorithm drastically reduces the number of passes required, obtaining a nearly optimal set of centers with a time complexity of O(log n).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] In practice, as few as five rounds are needed to reach a high-quality solution.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] After several rounds, the algorithm typically has O(log n) intermediate centers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] These are then assigned weights based on how many points are close to them and re-clustered, often using standard k-means++, to reduce the final set to exact k centers.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The slow "standard algorithm" for *k*-means clustering, and its associated expectation–maximization algorithm, is a special case of a Gaussian mixture model, specifically, the limiting case when fixing all covariances to be diagonal, equal and have infinitesimal small variance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Instead of small variances, a hard cluster assignment can also be used to show another equivalence of *k*-means clustering to a special case of "hard" Gaussian mixture modelling.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Another generalization of the *k*-means algorithm is the *k*-SVD algorithm, which estimates data points as a sparse linear combination of "codebook vectors".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] *k*-means corresponds to the special case of using a single codebook vector, with a weight of 1.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The relaxed solution of *k*-means clustering, specified by the cluster indicators, is given by principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The intuition is that *k*-means describe spherically shaped (ball-like) clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] If the data has 2 clusters, the line connecting the two centroids is the best 1-dimensional projection direction, which is also the first PCA direction.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Cutting the line at the center of mass separates the clusters (this is the continuous relaxation of the discrete cluster indicator).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] If the data have three clusters, the 2-dimensional plane spanned by three cluster centroids is the best 2-D projection.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This plane is also defined by the first two PCA dimensions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Well-separated clusters are effectively modelled by ball-shaped clusters and thus discovered by *k*-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Non-ball-shaped clusters are hard to separate when they are close.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] For example, two half-moon shaped clusters intertwined in space do not separate well when projected onto PCA subspace.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] *k*-means should not be expected to do well on this data.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] It is straightforward to produce counterexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by the principal directions.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Basic mean shift clustering algorithms maintain a set of data points the same size as the input data set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Initially, this set is copied from the input set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] All points are then iteratively moved towards the mean of the points surrounding them.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] A mean shift algorithm that is similar then to *k*-means, called *likelihood mean shift*, replaces the set of points undergoing replacement by the mean of all points in the input set that are within a given distance of the changing set.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] An advantage of mean shift clustering over *k*-means is the detection of an arbitrary number of clusters in the data set, as there is not a parameter determining the number of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Mean shift can be much slower than *k*-means, and still requires selection of a bandwidth parameter.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Under sparsity assumptions and when input data is pre-processed with the whitening transformation, *k*-means produces the solution to the linear independent component analysis (ICA) task.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] This aids in explaining the successful application of *k*-means to feature learning.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The set of squared error minimizing cluster functions also includes the *k*-medoids algorithm, an approach which forces the center point of each cluster to be one of the actual points, i.e., it uses medoids in place of centroids.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] Different implementations of the algorithm exhibit performance differences, with the fastest on a test data set finishing in 10 seconds, the slowest taking 25,988 seconds (~7 hours).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The differences can be attributed to implementation quality, language and compiler differences, different termination criteria and precision levels, and the use of indexes for acceleration.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The following implementations are available under Free/Open Source Software licenses, with publicly available source code.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/k-means-clustering] The following implementations are available under proprietary license terms, and may not have publicly available source code.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The silhouette value ranges from −1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] If most objects have a high value, then the clustering configuration is appropriate.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] If many points have a low or negative value, then the clustering configuration may have too many or too few clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] A clustering with an average silhouette width of over 0.7 is considered to be "strong", a value over 0.5 "reasonable", and over 0.25 "weak".
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] However, with an increasing dimensionality of the data, it becomes difficult to achieve such high values because of the curse of dimensionality, as the distances become more similar.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The silhouette score is specialized for measuring cluster quality when the clusters are convex-shaped, and may not perform well if the data clusters have irregular shapes or are of varying sizes.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The silhouette value can be calculated with any distance metric, such as Euclidean distance or Manhattan distance.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Assume the data have been clustered via any technique, such as k-medoids or k-means, into k clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] We then define the mean dissimilarity of point i to some cluster $C_{j}$ as the mean of the distance from i to all points in $C_{j}$ (where $C_{j}\neq C_{i}$ ).
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The cluster with the smallest mean dissimilarity is said to be the "neighboring cluster" of i because it is the next best fit cluster for point i .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Note that $a(i)$ is not clearly defined for clusters with size = 1, in which case we set $s(i)=0$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] This choice is arbitrary, but neutral in the sense that it is at the midpoint of the bounds, -1 and 1.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] For $s(i)$ to be close to 1 we require $a(i)\ll b(i)$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] As $a(i)$ is a measure of how dissimilar i is to its own cluster, a small value means it is well matched.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Furthermore, a large $b(i)$ implies that i is badly matched to its neighbouring cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Thus an $s(i)$ close to 1 means that the data is appropriately clustered.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] If $s(i)$ is close to -1, then by the same logic we see that i would be more appropriate if it was clustered in its neighbouring cluster.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] An $s(i)$ near zero means that the datum is on the border of two natural clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The mean $s(i)$ over all points of a cluster is a measure of how tightly grouped all the points in the cluster are.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Thus the mean $s(i)$ over all data of the entire dataset is a measure of how appropriately the data have been clustered.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] If there are too many or too few clusters, as may occur when a poor choice of k is used in the clustering algorithm (e.g., k-means), some of the clusters will typically display much narrower silhouettes than the rest.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Thus silhouette plots and means may be used to determine the natural number of clusters within a dataset.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] One can also increase the likelihood of the silhouette being maximized at the correct number of clusters by re-scaling the data using feature weights that are cluster specific.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] where ${\tilde {s}}\left(k\right)$ represents the mean $s(i)$ over all data of the entire dataset for a specific number of clusters k .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The silhouette coefficient describes the best possible clustering possible for a given number of clusters, as measured by the highest average *silhouette* score for all points in the dataset.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Computing the silhouette coefficient needs all ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})$ pairwise distances, making this evaluation much more costly than clustering with k-means.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] If the cluster centers are medoids (as in k-medoids clustering) instead of arithmetic means (as in k-means clustering), this is also called the medoid-based silhouette or medoid silhouette.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Instead of using the average silhouette to evaluate a clustering obtained from, e.g., k-medoids or k-means, we can try to directly find a solution that maximizes the Silhouette.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] We do not have a closed form solution to maximize this, but it will usually be best to assign points to the nearest cluster as done by these methods.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Perform the best swap and return to 3, otherwise stop if no improvement was found.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The loop in step 3 is executed for ${\mathcal {O}}(Nk)$ pairs, and involves computing the silhouette in ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})$ , hence this algorithm needs ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{3}ki)$ time, where i is the number of iterations.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Because this is a fairly expensive operation, the authors propose to also use the medoid-based silhouette, and call the resulting algorithm PAMMEDSIL.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] Batool et al. propose a similar algorithm under the name OSil, and propose a CLARA-like sampling strategy for larger data sets, that solves the problem only for a sub-sample.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] By adopting recent improvements to the PAM algorithm, FastMSC reduces the runtime using the medoid silhouette to just ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{2}i)$ .
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] By starting with a maximum number of clusters kmax and iteratively removing the worst center (in terms of a change in silhouette) and re-optimizing, the best (highest medoid silhouette) clustering can be automatically determined.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] As data structures can be reused, this reduces the computation cost substantially over repeatedly running the algorithm for different numbers of clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] This algorithm needs pairwise distances and is typically implemented with a pairwise distance matrix.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The ${\mathcal {O}}(N^{2})$ memory requirement is the main limiting factor for applying this to very large data sets.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] The traditional Silhouette score can be misleading when used to assess nested, concave-shaped clusters.
[src:cluster-analysis-stats/silhouette-clustering] In these contexts, a density-based version of the Silhouette score was proposed in 2014 by David Moulavi and colleagues in their work, and is called *DBCV index*.
